[{"id":"VR834506","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><div class=\"stimulus_reference\"><div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows three charges arranged particles of charge positive q in two different positions. In the initial positions, two charged particles are in a vertical line separated by a distance of d, represented by a vertical dashed line drawn between them. The third charged particle is very far to the right of the first two charged particles, and is along a horizontal dashed line that passes through the center of the vertical dashed line. In the final positions, the charged particles are at the corners of an equilateral triangle pointing to the right with a distance of d between the three charged particles.\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/578/VR834506.g01.svg\"/></div></div></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Two identical particles, each of positive charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive q\"><math alttext=\"positive q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mpadded><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi></mpadded></math></span></span>, are fixed in place a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>d</mi></math></span></span> apart. A third particle, also of charge <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"positive q\"><math alttext=\"positive q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mpadded><mo>+</mo><mi>q</mi></mpadded></math></span></span>, is initially at rest and located far away from the other two particles, as shown in the figure labeled “Initial Positions.” An external force then moves the third particle until it is at rest a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mi>d</mi></math></span></span> from the other particles, as shown in the figure labeled “Final Positions.” What is the relation between the electric potential energies <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub i\"><math alttext=\"U sub i\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub f\"><math alttext=\"U sub f\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>f</mi></msub></math></span></span> of the three-particle system in its initial and final configurations, respectively? What evidence or reasoning supports the claim?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR834506_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub f is greater than U sub i\"><math alttext=\"U sub f is greater than U sub i\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></math></span></span>. The external force is exerted in the direction of the third particle’s motion.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub f is greater than U sub i\"><math alttext=\"U sub f is greater than U sub i\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>&gt;</mo><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></math></span></span>. The first two particles exert a net electric force in the direction of the third particle’s motion.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub f equals U sub i\"><math alttext=\"U sub f equals U sub i\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></math></span></span>. The total net charge of the system does not change.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"U sub f equals U sub i\"><math alttext=\"U sub f equals U sub i\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>f</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>i</mi></msub></math></span></span>. The third particle is equidistant from the other two particles initially and finally.</p>"],"answer":0}]